            "
          >
            Pacific naval drill
          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image
          border-radius="10px"
          padding="10px 12px"
          width="600px"
          src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/china-russia-naval-drills-pacific.jpg"
          alt="Chinese and Russian naval officers stand in formation holding national flags in front of a warship during joint naval drills, highlighting growing military cooperation in the Pacific."
          href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com"
        />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>
              After the drills, China and Russia will conduct naval patrols in
              “relevant waters of the Pacific.” Source: People’s Liberation Army
              of China via My News</i
            >
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> China and Russia are conducting
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-4-aug-25-spotlight-h1-1-joint-naval-exercises?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >joint naval exercises</a
            >
            in the Sea of Japan, near Vladivostok, Russia. The three-day drill
            will focus on anti-submarine warfare, air defense, missile
            interception, and submarine rescue. Four Chinese warships, including
            the guided-missile destroyers Shaoxing and Urumqi, will participate
            in the exercises along with the Russian naval forces.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The background:</strong> This reflects the deepening
            military and strategic cooperation between China and Russia,
            particularly in the wake of Western sanctions on Russia. The two
            countries have conducted annual naval drills since 2012. While
            Beijing officially maintains a “<a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-4-aug-25-spotlight-h1-2-principled-neutrality?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >principled neutrality</a
            >”, it backs Moscow economically and diplomatically. These enhanced
            exercises allow China to practice maneuvering in a variety of
            geographies and climates.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The concern:</strong> Tokyo‌ warned about
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-4-aug-25-spotlight-h1-3-increased-strategic-cooperation?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >increased strategic cooperation</a
            >
            between Beijing and Moscow, as it poses a threat to Japan’s
            security, and hinted at a possible Ukraine-like war. They assert
            that Russia has stationed active military operations and violated
            its airspace. However, China has confirmed that the drills were not
            aimed at any country or related to the current international or
            regional situation.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
